T2d88,<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Problem Statement</strong>: Given a DAG( Directed Acyclic Graph ), print all the vertex of the graph in a topologically sorted order. If there are multiple solutions, print any.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Pre-req</strong>: DFS traversal, Graphs, Stack data structure.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:preformatted -->
<pre class="wp-block-preformatted"><strong>Example 1:</strong>
<strong>Input:</strong>
<strong><img width="341" height="446" src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/BckD9Ogx48ZGpT2pu4Nlhap7NqpUnY20RIul09YFCQRMzTC2P2NVRLqWzesaGvxR3sPGXVcw1RA1ATVA4GmEHSaMbgWo8GeBjMtPAGal9YRWislpnO8AgGw7R98PZw"></strong>
<strong>Output:</strong>
One of the solutions is 1,2,3,5,4</pre>
<!-- /wp:preformatted -->

<!-- wp:preformatted -->
<pre class="wp-block-preformatted"><strong>Example 2</strong>:
<strong>Input:</strong>
<strong><img width="343" height="291" src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/k0RRn4feh6urN0Mq49a3Hk2CqO6xf6WHt5So5c0BPg8SASENJs44O3KGH_3BW7XFlMeHTMDkku9NGk1ghqFRmWXefX2wHM65LvGkV68qHK-R-NijMxSFTPGLYbmffQ"></strong>
<strong>Output:</strong> One of the solution is 1,2,3,4,5,6</pre>
<!-- /wp:preformatted -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3><strong>Solution</strong></h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:paragraph {"textColor":"accent"} -->
<p class="has-accent-color has-text-color"><strong><em>Disclaimer</em>: </strong><em>Don't jump directly to the solution, try it out yourself first.</em></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Intuition:&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>-&gt; First of all let's understand Topological Sorting. It means linear ordering of vertices such that there is an edge u----&gt; v<strong>, </strong>u appears before v in the ordering.&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Suppose for a given graph,</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><img width="298" height="268" src="https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/wFeF2qf9qrTvnaywCNatyVuUTbKGKHtT9Nj2NsL7RXGllIwkt_JrojC2Y25_nk0J-Mt3_3ojnzmoruAFw3YPIn84FdMkQL9EnCY1k6KYPfs0JZmB6VCR_tiniLVgug"></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Some of the possible Topological orders can be:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->
<ol><li>&nbsp;5,4,2,3,1,0</li><li>&nbsp;4,5,2,3,1,0</li></ol>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>-&gt; In both cases we can see, that&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4-&gt;0 ( 4 appears before 0 ) , 5&gt;3 ( 5 appears before 3 ), …&nbsp;</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>-&gt; Similarly there can be<strong> multiple toposorts order for the given graph</strong> but the condition should be if there is an edge u-&gt;v then<strong> u should always appear before v.</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>-&gt; Topological Sorting is applicable only for <strong>DAG(Directed Acyclic Graph)</strong>. Why is it so?</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Because of the following reasons:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->
<ol><li>For Undirected graphs ,only u-&gt;v is not applicable . It cannot be sure whether the edge is between u to v or v to u ( u-v ) .</li><li>In a cyclic graph there will always be a dependency factor . You cannot make sure that you can have linear ordering of vertices.</li></ol>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>-&gt; Finally, now you have a clear understanding of what Topological Sorting is. We will be using the<strong> DFS(Depth First Search)</strong> method to solve the problem. What we will be doing is for each vertex we will explore its adjacent vertex. After exploring, we will store the current vertex in a data structure to maintain Topo Sort.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Approach:</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>We will be using the following data structure to get Topo sort:</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:list {"ordered":true} -->
<ol><li>Visited Vector - To store visit of each vertex</li><li>Stack - To maintain the topo sort order.</li></ol>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><img width="624" height="791" src="https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/whYcMaLKUMgGRpbI2rE7RFqaOC_cM27jR4Vm-cGkshzg4cFoCjIjdzEkvfRwjLQlcWtQa0i9iI0dcWk6NMNmAqHnbQnoPtNQ5Pnnpk87O0sTGBUxp80EWlUhbtSj6A"></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><img width="624" height="828" src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/YJK0WhiUqWdLWmS0e-C6fyv25FaaGM_GO_u6g9PYHRcMh15alfCDtFd5e6Bwhha8-jDPhscdmOLRhwmvj5Jk6bQQvd7eFzKh6Oq2z7gYH-G6K8-2r9vfOs65LuoWLA"></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Did you notice something while using Stack? Just because there was an edge from u to v. Dfs call will go from u to v. The 1st dfs (v) will get over first and then dfs(u). Here we are making sure that if u-&gt;v, then we will <strong>first push v into the stack and then u will be pushed</strong>. This is how Topological order is maintained in the Stack.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Code:</strong></p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

